the demand for biofuel and the effects of biofuel policies on agricultural price uncertainty. Also discussed are genetically engineered crops, which are assuming an increasingly important role in arbitrating tensions between energy production, environmental protection, and the global food supply. Other contributions discuss the major effects of genetic engineering on worldwide food markets. By addressing some of the most challenging topics at the intersection of agriculture and biotechnology, this volume informs crucial debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAgricultural biotechnology -- Government policy -- United States. 0aAgricultural subsidies -- Government policy -- United States. 0aAgriculture and energy -- Government policy -- United States. 0aAgriculture and state -- United States. 0aBiomass energy -- Government policy -- United States. 0aCrop insurance -- United States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aagriculture, biotechnology, biofuel, public policy, insurance, crop processors, farmers, farming, agricultural price uncertainty, genetically engineered crops, environmental protection, global food supply, markets, subsidies, biomass, risk response, nonfiction, politics, economics, land use, energy, production, commodities.1 aBabcock, Bruce A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckman, Jayson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Xiaoguang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodhue, Rachael E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin, Barry K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraff Zivin, Joshua S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHertel, Thomas W., econtributor.4ctb4https://i